Introduction¶

In this project, the correlations between various accidental mortality rates will be investigated for different countries in years 2002 and 2004. The accidental mortality rate variables include falls, burns, poisoning, and drownings mortality (age-adjusted and expressed per 100,000 people). The datasets were provided from Gapminder under the indicator names 'Burns deaths (per 100,000 people)', 'Drownings (per 100,000 people)', 'Falls, Deaths (per 100,000 people)', and 'Poisonings, deaths (per 100,000 people)'.

The questions we will be aiming to answer are the following:

  • What is the most common cause of accidental mortality in the world of the variables analyzed?
  • Has accidental mortality rates in the world improved from 2002 to 2004?
  • Which countries have the lowest and highest accidental death rates?
  • How are the accidental mortality rate variables correlated to one another?
    • </ul

Combining into a Single Dataset¶

The data is contained in four different datasets, so we will need to merge the data into a single set and maybe perform some cleaning if required.

In [7]:
# For all the datasets, we will change the column names into something more descriptive so we don't confuse the columns.
df_burn.columns = ['country', 'burn_2002', 'burn_2004']
df_drowning.columns = ['country', 'drowning_2002', 'drowning_2004']
df_fall.columns = ['country', 'fall_2002', 'fall_2004']
df_poisoning.columns = ['country', 'poisoning_2002', 'poisoning_2004']

df_combined['poisoning_2004'] = df_poisoning['poisoning_2004']

# The data seems clean with the desired datatypes and no null values. However, we also want to fill in zero values with
# with the mean because we assume that zero values are null points. This is required because when we plot the countries 
# with the least accidental mortality rate, we do not want these to show up. We will use the replace function [3] for this.
df_combined['burn_2002'].replace(0, df_combined['burn_2002'].mean(), inplace=True)
df_combined['burn_2004'].replace(0, df_combined['burn_2004'].mean(), inplace=True)
df_combined['drowning_2002'].replace(0, df_combined['drowning_2002'].mean(), inplace=True)
df_combined['drowning_2004'].replace(0, df_combined['drowning_2004'].mean(), inplace=True)
df_combined['fall_2002'].replace(0, df_combined['fall_2002'].mean(), inplace=True)
df_combined['fall_2004'].replace(0, df_combined['fall_2004'].mean(), inplace=True)
df_combined['poisoning_2002'].replace(0, df_combined['poisoning_2002'].mean(), inplace=True)
df_combined['poisoning_2004'].replace(0, df_combined['poisoning_2004'].mean(), inplace=True)

Now that we have cleaned the data, we will try to systematically answer the questions we are aiming to answer with data visualizations.

What is the most common cause of accidental mortality in the world of the variables analyzed? Has accidental mortality rates in the world improved from 2002 to 2004?¶

To investigate these questions, we will look at the mean and some summary statistics of the data for each accidental mortality cause in both 2002 and 2004. We will then plot this in a double bar chart so we can visualize which accidental mortality causes have the highest global mean for both years.

# We will plot a double bar chart [2] of the mortality rates of each of the variables for 2002 and 2004. We will also 
#   create a labels variable to hold the label names. 
labels = ['Burn Deaths', 'Drowning Deaths', 'Fall Deaths', 'Poisoning Deaths']
plt.barh([1,4,7,10], df_2002.iloc[:,[1,2,3,4]].mean(), label='2002')
plt.barh([2,5,8,11], df_2004.iloc[:,[1,2,3,4]].mean(), label='2004')
plt.title('Accidental Mortality Rates for Different Causes in 2002 and 2004');
plt.xlabel('Mortality (age-adjusted, per 100,000)');
plt.yticks([1.5,4.5,7.5,10.5], labels);
plt.legend();

Now that the data has been plotted as a double bar chart, we can conveniently observe the trends in the data and make tentative conclusions about the data.

Which countries have the highest and lowest accidental mortality rates?¶

Next, we will investigate which countries have the highest and lowest accidental mortality rates. We have 192 countries in our dataset, so there is too much data to visualize if we plot all the countries in one chart. Instead, we will look at the top 10 countries with the highest and lowest accidental death rates in 2004. We choose 2004 as the only data to analyze because it is more modern, and therefore probably a better indicator of the current situation.

Conclusions¶

We can draw a few interesting conclusions from the data analysis. Of the four variables, drownings seems to be the most common cause of accidental mortality in the world based on the mean, followed by falls second, poisonings third, and burns last. However, from the summary statistics, we can see that poisoning has the maximum value for mortality and a higher variability, which suggests that drowning may be main cause of accidental mortality in certain countries.

Globally, the rate of accidental mortalities have also decreased from 2002 to 2004. For all categories, the mean mortality rate decreased. This may be because of improved safety standards around the world, although further investigation is necessary to prove this

From the bar charts, we can see which countries have the highest and lowest mortality rates for each category in 2004. Singapore, Israel, and Italy have some of the least burn deaths and least drowning deaths. Additionally, Singapore is also on the least poisoning deaths chart. Countries with high accidental deaths from burns and falls include Laos, Iraq, and India. Additionally, we can see that the countries with the highest accidental mortality rates include Kazakhstan, Russia, and Belarus, while those with the least include Israel, Georgia, and Dominican Republic.

Lastly, from the matrix of scatter plots, we see slight positive correlation for most of the accidental mortality rates in 2002 and 2004. This suggests that countries that a higher incidence of one kind of accidental death may also be more prone to another kind of accidental death. This may be because of a third variable that plays a role - a possible reason is that countries that invest less in accident prevention have higher accidental death mortalities. However, more investigation is needed to support this conclusion.

There are some limitations to the analysis that should be pointed out. During the data cleaning process, zero values were replaced with the mean, which is inaccurate. It was assumed that zero values were an indicator of the absence of data instead of the value actually being zero, since it seems unlikely that a country has a zero accidental mortality rate. Also, we should consider the data quality and integrity - how accurately have the data been recorded and are there uniform recording procedures for every country? We can also look into how mortality rate is calculated, as the file mentions that it is age-adjusted. Finally, the trends found in this analysis can only suggest correlations, and we should be careful about implying causation merely based on the trends. Furthermore, additional statistical techniques such as regression can be applied, although it was decided that it is out of the scope of this project.
